        <h2>1. Unity ShaderLab Cheatsheet – Introduction</h2>
        <p>This Unity ShaderLab cheatsheet provides a structured, production-oriented reference for technical artists working with hand-written shaders in Unity. Whether you’re transitioning from ShaderGraph or diving into hand-written shaders, this guide provides you with an in-depth look at shader code structure, property declaration, and how the GPU processes shader code. We’ll also explore special ShaderLab features such as drawer attributes, tags, and SubShaders, and discuss how these concepts vary across render pipelines (Built-in, URP, HDRP).</p>
        <h3>Unity ShaderLab Cheatsheet: What is ShaderLab in Unity?</h3>
        <p>ShaderLab is Unity’s shader definition language used to structure passes, render states and connect CG/HLSL code.</p>
        <div class="atlas-compare">
          <div class="atlas-compare__column">
            <div class="atlas-compare__badge" data-side="left">
              // SYSTEM_CORE: CG_HLSL_PROGRAM
            </div>
            <div class="atlas-compare__content">
              <span class="atlas-compare__concept">CG Shader</span>
              <p>Uses the Cg/HLSL language to write low-level shader programs. A shader file typically contains execution sections enclosed by <code>CGPROGRAM</code> and <code>ENDCG</code> (or modern <code>HLSLPROGRAM</code> blocks for URP/HDRP) that are compiled directly into raw GPU bytecode instructions.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="atlas-compare__divider"></div>
          <div class="atlas-compare__column">
            <div class="atlas-compare__badge" data-side="right">
              // SYSTEM_WRAPPER: SHADERLAB_PIPELINE
            </div>
            <div class="atlas-compare__content">
              <span class="atlas-compare__concept">ShaderLab</span>
              <p>A Unity-specific declarative wrapper that defines properties, SubShaders, passes, and fallback states. It orchestrates how your low-level program interacts with the material Inspector UI and binds to the internal rendering execution pipeline.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="atlas-notice">
          <span class="atlas-notice__header">[ SYSTEM NOTICE: RENDER PIPELINES STRATEGY SHIFT ]</span>
          <p><strong>IMPORTANT (2026):</strong> Unity has officially shifted its core development strategy. <strong>URP</strong> is now the primary scalable foundation for all future graphics investments, while <strong>HDRP</strong> enters maintenance mode, and <strong>BiRP</strong> deprecation officially begins in Unity 6.5.</p>
        </div>
        <h3>Timeline & Major Pipeline Iterations</h3>
        <h3>[ 2024 ] Legacy Cleansing & Core Convergence</h3>
        <p>Focus on stabilizing Scriptable Render Pipelines (SRP) under the hood and phasing out old workflows:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>CGPROGRAM Deprecation:</strong> Legacy blocks are fully deprecated in URP/HDRP. Writing <code>HLSLPROGRAM / ENDHLSL</code> is mandatory to ensure modern shader target compatibility and avoid compilation faults in SRP.</li>
          <li><strong>URP 3D Textures (v12+):</strong> Native support and sampling mechanics for 3D Textures are stabilized, enabling complex volumetric effects within the Universal pipeline.</li>
          <li><strong>Render Graph Architecture:</strong> Initial framework convergence under the hood to align URP and HDRP execution passes.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><b>Key Resources:</b> <a class="atlas-blueprint-link" href="https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/shader-shaderlab-code-blocks.html" target="_blank">ShaderLab Code Blocks</a></p>
        <h3>[ 2025 ] Unity 6 Production Lifecycle</h3>
        <p>The release of Unity 6 brings architectural optimization and high-fidelity rendering paths to URP:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>GPU Resident Drawer & Render Graph:</strong> Massive draw-call and CPU-overhead reduction via hardware-driven data residency and automatic frame-graph optimization.</li>
          <li><strong>Unity 6.1 (Deferred+ & VRS):</strong> Introduction of the <code>Deferred+</code> rendering path in URP alongside native Variable Rate Shading (VRS) for aggressive modern hardware optimization.</li>
          <li><strong>Advanced Feature Reflow:</strong> Motion Vector passes, Lights 2D upgrades, and enhanced Alpha Processing bring URP closer to feature parity with old HDRP standards.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><b>Key Resources:</b> <a class="atlas-blueprint-link" href="https://docs.unity3d.com/6000.0/Documentation/Manual/WhatsNewUnity6.html" target="_blank">Unity 6 What's New</a> <span class="atlas-footer-block__support-divider">|</span> <a class="atlas-blueprint-link" href="https://docs.unity3d.com/Packages/com.unity.render-pipelines.universal@17.0/changelog/CHANGELOG.html" target="_blank">URP Changelog 17.0.x</a></p>
        <h3>[ 2026 ] The Single Architecture Push</h3>
        <p>The definitive pivot. Unity consolidates all graphic engineering resources into a single scalable engine:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>URP as the Master Pipeline:</strong> Receives high-end extensions previously locked to HDRP: Physical Light Units, Auto-Exposure, Physical Sky managers, Screen Space Reflections (SSR), and real-time Global Illumination.</li>
          <li><strong>HDRP Maintenance Mode:</strong> Frozen at current visual feature sets. Engineering is strictly limited to stability, bug fixes, and platform-specific compilation (including <strong>Nintendo Switch 2</strong> preview support in v6.5).</li>
          <li><strong>BiRP EOL (End of Life):</strong> Deprecation formally begins in Unity 6.5. Legacy projects are supported through Unity 6.7 LTS (until late 2028/2029 for Enterprise), but all Asset Store assets and documentation transition to URP defaults.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><b>Official Sources:</b> <a class="atlas-blueprint-link" href="https://unity.com/topics/render-pipelines-strategy-for-2026" target="_blank">Strategy Roadmap</a> <span class="atlas-footer-block__support-divider">|</span> <a class="atlas-blueprint-link" href="https://discussions.unity.com/t/render-pipelines-strategy-for-2026/1710004" target="_blank">Unity Forum Discussion</a></p>
