        <h2>6. Unity Render Pipeline Fundamentals</h2>
        <p>Unity utilizes three distinct rendering architectures, each tailored to different performance requirements, hardware targets, and pipeline capabilities.</p>
        <h3>Key Unity Rendering Architectures</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Built-In Render Pipeline (BIRP):</strong> The legacy rendering system using Cg/HLSL. It relies on <code>CGPROGRAM</code> blocks and includes <code>UnityCG.cginc</code>. Best suited for legacy projects or older mobile hardware where optimization must be manually tuned.</li>
          <li><strong>Universal Render Pipeline (URP):</strong> The modern, highly scalable replacement for BIRP. It requires <code>HLSLPROGRAM</code> blocks and utilizes modern HLSL includes (such as <code>Core.hlsl</code>). Features include a single-pass forward renderer, a dedicated 2D Renderer, and native Shader Graph support. Highly recommended for cross-platform deployments spanning mobile, PC, and consoles.</li>
          <li><strong>High Definition Render Pipeline (HDRP):</strong> A physically-based rendering (PBR) pipeline built specifically for high-end fidelity. It heavily utilizes compute shaders, advanced lighting models, and volumetric effects. Best suited for AAA-grade visual productions on high-performance PC and console hardware.</li>
        </ul>
